Republican Party's strategy against Obama's re-election
Republican leaders have justified their policies with the necessity of combating electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, describes such fraud as a myth that election fraud is less common in the U.S. than the number of people who die after a lightning strike.
Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in the past decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections.
And in this spirit, most U.S. governments have been promulgating new laws since 2009 that make the process of election or enrollment more difficult.
This phenomenon saw a boom after the November 2010 election, during which 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states were added.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the right to vote in 41 states were submitted in 2011 alone.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws restrict the period for early elections, invalidate the right to register on the electoral list on the day of the election and deprive citizens with a criminal record of their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state had asked voters to present a photo ID.
The first state to introduce this requirement was Indiana.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States ratified the Indian Constitution.
The Republican authorities were in a hurry to extend this procedure to other states.
In the past two years, bills in 34 states have supported such laws to force voters to submit photo IDs.
It should be noted that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not own a photo ID issued by the government office of their state.
In addition, about five million new voters did not have such identity cards in 2012.
In addition, obtaining the required ID often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new constraints are disproportionately affecting young people, members of minorities and people with low incomes.
25% of African Americans, 15% of people with income under $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 therefore do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their propensity for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their school in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who elect Republican candidates to use the cards issued by those clubs in elections.
Until 2004, no state required a nationality certificate in the elections.
The first such request was made by Arizona.
Since 2011, about twelve states have passed laws that require voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are apparently aimed at limiting the number of votes from the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer the democratic side.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states voted to repeal voter registration on election day.
They also restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to register.
These restrictions have their consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general elections, campaigns to register voters helped register about 10 million people.
However, the measures taken after 2009 caused a 17% decrease in the number of new voters registered in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early elections.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, African Americans made up 33% of voters who voted in advance, even though there were only 13% of African American voters in that state.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
They made up only 11% of all voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who accounted for 76% of all voters, made up only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Democratic governors blocked several bills with their veto.
In order to suspend the most controversial laws, the U.S. Attorney General even intervened.
The damage has been partly reduced.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have adopted laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules will undeniably make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics speak primarily of the presumption of approved laws and consider them a clear attempt to influence the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
The Brennan Center’s 2011 report shows that the states where these laws were passed represent 171 of the 270 votes in the electorate necessary to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain today: these new provisions will have an adverse impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
