Higgs Boson Examined
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson sparked a legitimate upheaval last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in a mechanism that is responsible for all the matter in the universe.
And it is also the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "worst" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - which, however, has not yet been empirically observed.
However, physicists do not yet have 100% certainty that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have an entirely new particle at our disposal that is very similar to the Higgs boson as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week during the big physical congress in Kyoto is more of a confirmation, but all the data is still missing so that we can have absolute certainty.
However, let's assume it's the Higgs boson, because the risks of mistakes seem small, and let's look at what's really going on.
There is an unquestionable law in this world, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly constitutes them.
It also divides physical particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently adhere to Pauli’s principle.
And at the other end are bosons, vile anarchists, who value nothing at all - certainly not this principle, which means that they can be at the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way, absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: the mesons, which we leave here unnoticed, and the "power particles", with which the great forces of nature are spread and with which the way of Higgs's bosons is the most common.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it is thanks to a boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of an electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in that particular place, similar to a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) arises, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "carriers of force".
A more stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, but the difference is that another field, the Higgs field, needs to be "disrupted" to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, very high energy values must be achieved, just as with the frozen level of the pond, which is only lightened by a very large boulder.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge part accelerator as an accelerator in the CERN lab - a large hadron accelerator with matching bundles is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
The electromagnetic field does not react with all particles or materials.
Some, for example, magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep itself on the refrigerator.
And the same is true that not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do so have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let's look at it) do not.
And Mrs. Nováková asks, what are all these researches for, what are they "bringing us"?
From the point of view of science, it is a validation of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to undergo an examination of any inconsistency between observations and predictions of SM.
In addition, not a few physicists literally want to be able to find them, because the slightest difference could open up the space of "new physics" and fill some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge shortcomings, does not bring any clarification of gravity (ouha!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of space matter (again ouha!).
However, the CERN facility has not yet revealed such contradictions.
Answers
The responses of these researches in the daily life of Mr and Mrs Novák can only be very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
Look: at the very beginning of the 1960s, laser pioneers in Bell’s laboratories had no idea of the revolution that their work would bring about.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing more.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (the previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said - the laser was initially considered such a "laboratory toy".
Just imagine it...
And in addition, the application can also result from all the tools that surround research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work focused on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle initially did not plan to do so, now serves as the “eye” of all digital cameras in the world and won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities around LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it does mean that you really never know...
Palliative care - The best way to get out of life... <0x7C> Le Devoir
Through its Commission for a Decent Death, Quebec has recently been involved in a delicate end-of-life issue.
