Le Devoir tried to take a closer look at the issue.
Less than a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that fed him gave him a two-year delay.
"They gave me five years to live and it's seven," he says without emotion on his bed in the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's still a shock, you can't prepare for this," he adds.
The disease has done its job: immense weakness makes it impossible for him to go to the toilet on his own or just to eat on his own.
Resigned, he looks at the deliciously-looking breakfast and agrees that we will help him eat.
He is brave and even smiles, talks to strangers who stop at him, brings him medicines, offers a bath.
Courage for ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to get rid of diarrhea, it humiliates me," he confides.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
“All your life, you learn that men urinate,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois.
Returning to the stage of a child is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the abilities of which person," the psychologist says.
In the opinion of a number of people engaged in palliative care, crucial moments take place in the very core of such a return.
Patients who enter a home with Victor-Gadbois palliative care are all suffering from cancer.
Their prognosis is a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, a team of doctors and nurses who take care of them does not provide them with so-called "medical" care.
In the case of Ms. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "of suffocation in full consciousness".
But the disease allowed me to discover my children.
"I have good kids," he adds.
"I don't have any desires in my life anymore," she says, and then she lets us put on her breathing apparatus.
However, he is still looking forward to the last visit of his son from Italy in the coming days.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, in cooperation with a group of volunteers, body care is provided with the help of nutrition.
This is what palliative care looks like, which occurs if nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one bed of palliative care per 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if we realize that we're all going to die one day.
Here life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at home.
Whether it is the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, you can give him, for example, a pinch of brandy or pepsi, according to his taste.
Diabetics no longer need to monitor their sugar levels.
Death is a part of everyday life.
Last night they brought a beer to Mr. X, who died later that night.
This morning, his son will have a beer in honor of his deceased father.
"We help patients as well as their loved ones," says Nathalie Savard, director of care services.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, days pass one after another, but they do not resemble each other.
Alongside a thirty-nine-year-old man who rejoices at the last meeting with his family thoroughly laid on pillows while drinking in his honor, a thirty-six-year-old man tragically dies surrounded by his parents, his wife, and two young children, in order to try all of them.
"For six months, there have always been three to five beds, which are designed for people with cancer under 45 years old," says Dr. Christiane Martel with concern.
53% of patients who come to Victor-Gadbois’ home come from their homes, and 47% come from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care that is designed to alleviate the suffering as soon as the patient reaches the final stage of his life, whether it be at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of the Grand Montréal Area, specialize more less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is this fundamental inaccessibility of health care in Quebec that has led a number of palliative care specialists to fear the adoption of a law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, the manifesto has been signed by top palliative care professionals such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in which they show their disapproval of such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not powerful enough to ensure that all people have access to quality palliative care before it is possible to agree to euthanasia.
She says she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in an emergency room in enormous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
He fears that patients will not be asked to be killed because they are not receiving proper care.
And at the same time, a number of oncologists take care of their patients until the last minute, regardless of the adverse prognosis.
Hopes for Hélène Richard's survival were already minimal when she left the demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was finishing treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she told us.
And yet she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care.
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their attending physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when a team of palliative paws relieved their pain.
However, it must be said that palliative care is definitely not all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Grand Montréal area, patients are preventing pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use a palliative sedative, which sleeps the patient until the moment he dies, whether it is a shock or if the sedative is given to him permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
A patient who is not relieved of pain will have an increasing chance of accessing palliative sedatives.
Those who are not given sedatives always say the same thing: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to give me euthanasia,” it means “I want you to get rid of my pain.”
