And yet the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this fact in its report on virtual finance, which was released in October.
Bitcoin refers to "most successful virtual money", "competitive dollar and euro" and "current money period".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is used as "credits" for progress in a video game, which a person gains through the game or which he can buy (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
Each month, however, the central authority monitors and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are bookkeepers of current accounts, controllers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses using email.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
The information set related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of current accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction into this book.
It is done by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, the solver of which, like a temporary central banker, will have the right to complete this additional line.
This is the stage of cutting a file; i.e. transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital print.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then they "cut" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that provides a particular print (value zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes will easily check its accuracy.
The transaction will then appear indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the imprint.
If the user would like to pay twice the same money very quickly (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, because each has a different imprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this reward is divided regularly into two, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but it can be divided by up to one hundred million, so there is room for margins.
The difficulty of a given task also increases with increasing levels of computation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been hacked and stored bitcoins have been stolen.
“The hole used is not about the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also controls the possibility of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But this also applies to cash.
Significant players like Wikipedia are refusing gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the book of accounts and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not take place.
In November, "huge discounts" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who is involved in converting bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but uses a Bitcoin system to verify transactions that are therefore cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up for merchants, where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to give an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that it already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement towards questioning hierarchical systems and the transition to more horizontal systems.
“Before Bitcoin is implemented, it will take a while, but 2013 could be crucial,” he predicts.
In addition, the ECB’s report envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are currently considered to be increased if this type of money is successful.
We've left Afghanistan.
What's next?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and U.S. troops are expected to follow by the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to take control of its territory and for the Afghans to choose their own future and not expect everything from us.
The people in the Afghan countryside suffered the most damage, which we punished because we considered them terrorists.
And we, too, have lost 88 killed soldiers, and all those wounded and mutilated.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former leaders who have fled to Pakistan, but they are often the countrymen who deny the presence of foreign armies as in Soviet times.
They only want to defend their ancient and archaic traditions, even though they were joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
They are now experiencing tolerance and frequent help from local insurgents, but if Western forces withdraw, their support will decline.
The departure of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I watched from the peaks of the mountains planted with almonds thanks to the French loans, took place in an orderly manner.
Convoys of trucks and armored vehicles arrived in Kabul without being attacked by air escort helicopters.
Since the end of 2014, the Taliban will no longer be so active in Kabul.
Since their unstoppable progress between 1994 and 1996, conditions have changed considerably.
The Kabul was empty at the time and the land was in blood and fire as a result of fighting between different resistance groups.
Their takeover of the country was then considered a kind of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghans paid the price for the darkness of these villagers, who were completely controlled by al-Qaida, but their situation has not improved until now.
Former mujahideen, the Afghan government and the current Taliban all agree to try to keep women in a subordinate position.
The main ranks of the war against Soviet troops returned to power in 2001.
They became businessmen, seized state land, sold as construction land to refugees from Iran and Pakistan, and exploited huge U.S. contracts for subcontractors.
