The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural aid from local communities in the province of Kapisa.
In order to free these farmers from insurrections led by foreign groups, they wish, in their words, to obtain a small amount of civil aid in their favour, which would be properly controlled and directly affected by them.
Difficult work on the Egyptian constitution
President Muhammad Mursi is playing another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the promulgation of a constitution, which temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, irrespective of everyone else's opinion, that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave this assembly two more months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, which has been supplemented many times, weakening the country’s constitutional stability and leading to legal disputes.
This new initiative only further strengthened the fragmentation of the country.
From the point of view of the opposition, the president remains in his “autocratic delirium”, continues to “break his word” and “step the law”.
His supporters, however, assure that it is a means to overcome the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum will be held in two weeks.
It is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of the text to the Egyptians to clarify article by article.
It is also a way for the president to regain national and democratic legitimacy while the whole country is upset by the protests.
As confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor.
Especially because this swiftly organised vote puts the Egyptian people ahead of an ultimatum: "Either you approve my text, or I will retain unlimited powers", which should otherwise end once the new constitution is approved.
And in this special atmosphere yesterday, 85 MEPs of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, shortly before the proclamation of the constitution, they knocked on the door with the fact that they did not have the opportunity to assert their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their move.
In order to achieve sleep capacity, 11 people from the ranks of substitutes were quickly added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising, then, that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
The commentators further suspended the fact that one of the few disputes that day revolved around... the hour of prayer, when some members of the committee held the view that the hour in the meeting room was not set correctly.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject matter of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution and stipulates that "the principles of sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term "principle" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for the rest of Egyptian society.
“Hypocriticism,” argue the liberals, who see in it only a vocabulary problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts the al-Azhar University with an advisory role, in particular on issues of checking compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "persons called to express themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
The beginnings of theocracy can be seen in this.”
The fears of liberals are even more aroused by the fact that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there has been no specific religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not Ulamites, but university workers, many of them graduated in French schools," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing the work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be contradictions with regard to the interpretation of Article 220, since the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question may arise to what extent civilian judges are competent to express themselves.”
The text approved yesterday has been heavily criticized, in addition to the religious pages, because of the expanded powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant reduction in the number of Muslims compared to the previous regime.
Another controversial point: the powers entrusted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military representatives, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
In addition, the military courts will not ban the use of civilians, as demanded by the human rights association.
These associations speak of their doubts in the context of the text, which they consider to be anti-freedom.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and the insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, in particular for the press.
In addition, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to make a televised speech last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then protest on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy sites, the navel of the world and the sea from a saturated solution of salt
The promised land combines the greatness of Biblical truths, modern comfort and the inviolability of nature.
AaF has identified five of the most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Worshiping the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is claimed that God’s mercy will descend upon all who enter this “basin.”
And Galilee - the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here, too, Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers will follow the Way of the Pain or the Cross of Jesus (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the judgment was held, passes through the streets of the Old City and leads to the Temple of the Tomb of God on the Mount of Golgotha - to the place of crucifixion, to the anointing stone and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built at the place where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew, from which they made a cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for Jews - the Wall of Lamentations, the rest of the temple, which was destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
According to tradition, here people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Make a path in a vertical
The ruins of the fortress Masada remained from a secret hiding place from the enemy that Herod the Great built in 25 B.C.E. for his family.
The ruin is located on the cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are engaged in mountaineering can get to it by their own forces.
The rest will be transported by cable car to this historic mountain.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
A shuttle bus takes tourists to this ski paradise from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the top of the mountain.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are about 300 museums in the country.
You can’t visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, which is located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It contains ancient Kumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and approximately 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
His paintings are widely represented by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akkon you can visit the Al Basha Spa Museum, which presents to visitors several rooms of ancient Turkish spas with figurines of spa users and spa caregivers of the time.
Caesarea is worth a visit to the unique private museum of Ralli, where you can admire the statues of Dalí and Roden.
There are no guides or souvenir shops here.
Admission is free and gifts are strictly refused.
The Fifth Museum – the Yad Vashem Museum in Tel Aviv – tells the story of one of the most dramatic parts of history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go inside – and you find yourself in total darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of the children of the Jews, and the names of the countries in which they perished.
Ukraine is also mentioned here.
Improving Your Health
The three main spas in Israel are located on the coasts of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, aquaparks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, in the Red Sea you can swim even in the winter months, because the water temperature in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
The Dead Sea is by the way the most peculiar sea in the world, located at the lowest continental point of the planet - at the level of 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated salt solution that easily keeps on the surface even people who can not swim.
The surrounding countryside is unrealistically beautiful.
Go here to undergo treatment using salt water - brine, and healing mud, which can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to cure the smelly nerves.
Touch the mysterious past of a long time ago
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through them.
Mentions of this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it is the place where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists really love the strollers by the lanes, named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you squeeze yourself against the walls in the alley of "your" sign, luck will favorably favor you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "get" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman prosecutors including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully refurbished theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, by word of mouth
If you are going to Israel, you do not have to worry about your imperfect English: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
On the way, it is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is about 3.8 shekels).
There are mainly buses, but in Jerusalem there is a high-speed tram and in the city of Haifa there is the only subway line in the country with six stations connecting the lower city with the upper one.
It's basically an underground cable car.
Traveling by all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can drive for 1.5 hours with a transfer.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on the Sabbath.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, he stops working in markets, shops and in public transport.
And Sunday morning starts the working week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels you only get kosher meals: except for pork, seafood, fish without scales and meals that contain a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a large selection of dishes from lamb and beef, soups and desserts, prepared from coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, various types of sauces, ground beans balls - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israel.
On the other hand, there are a lot of fed cats, which gracefully "walk according to their taste".
In the evening you can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Leading cats love populated places and are eager to indulge in any kind of goodness.
Car rental will cost from $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 per day (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - $15 per day.
And renting a bike will cost about 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Explained numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
To get to know the country and rest most citizens came from the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
The Promised Land was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the visa waiver on February 9, 2011.
"Great and powerful" will announce in Moscow: emigrants will save money on language
While MPs and human rights defenders are still debating the law on compulsory language exams, fraudsters have already appeared in the country selling "falsified" certificates
Every year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make enough money to support families at home.
On 1 December, a law came into force that required every migrant to pass the Russian language test.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing and municipal economy, lifestyle and retail sectors.
However, the FMS promises that over time, the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of language knowledge, but also of Russian history and the fundamentals of law.
Language proficiency will also need to be confirmed in order to obtain and renew a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law does not apply to people who have successfully obtained a certificate and obtained an academic diploma until the dissolution of the USSR in 1991.
Use, Condemnation and Protection of Rights
The network of test sites will work under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of Friendship between Nations, the Moscow State University, the State University of St. Petersburg and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take exams in all cities; as of today, more than 160 such centers are open in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by Members of the State Duma and FMS (Federal Migration Service).
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders were able to ask the question many times in the press: and what does it actually bring?
What will change the obligation to know the language for the Russians and for the visitors themselves?
First and foremost - according to the representatives of the migration services - this will allow to reduce the number of people suffering from the result of "slavery work."
Many people today are talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, chairman of the board of FMS Russia in Tajikistan.
The protection of their rights should start before they leave.
Only the system of organized recruitment will allow 90% to solve the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise in emigrants without a profession, without an education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowledge of the language, says Sebelev, the future migrant is condemned to clashes with dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "recipe" to terrible, tight shelters in which he and dozens of others, like himself, will suffer for 12 months without food and documents.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrant workers.
"They promise them one thing in their homeland, but on arrival they will be defrauded, they will confiscate their passports, they will not pay the promised wages," confirms MS Tolib Sharipov, the head of the main Tajik labour migration administration.
Don't freak out!
The less so is the fact that many citizens of Central Asian republics who intend to go to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to get to, but they do not even have experience with the given work.
Of course, it is not their fault, but rather their misfortune: only very few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get at least an adequate basic education.
After all, their families also need something to feed their children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly dressed, shoes and equipped for school.
As children reach productive age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language, it is difficult - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
It is true that, with regard to the language test law, human rights defenders point to one important point.
Testing will only be carried out on those migrants who have legal status.
If they don't have it, they won't pass the exams or get any other official job.
In the meantime, the majority of migrant workers live illegally in Russia, just as they did in the past.
"Welcome, or Unauthorized Entry Banned"
Many of the incoming workers say that getting official status in our country is not easy.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all the language difficulties.
Legalization, in addition, costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But false registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
Russian police officers know that we basically have fake documents, without registration, and that leads to cases of blackmail.
"They require a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," Umed Chuschadamov, a Tajik citizen, told reporters about his experience.
"Come on, don't be greedy, buy yourself a painting."
On the first day of the law on language, it was found that it is not only the documents of registration of migrants that are false.
FMS employees have already seized several false certificates of passing a language test.
Counterfeit documents are printed on ordinary colour printers.
Of course, they did not get to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, in the hope of making it easier to pass the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times the amount of taking the official test: it will cost the migrant workers three thousand rubles.
The main task in the near future is to secure the system against corruption, so that workers can not simply buy documents, both government officials and human rights defenders agree.
So far, the government has promised foreign workers who failed the tests for the first time, the time it takes to take a Russian-language basics course.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas where active interaction with people is not required.
MVD (Ministry of the Interior) does not put the illegal arms market into circulation
The proportion of criminal offences with the use of legally held weapons is very low
The MVD of Russia is presenting a proposal to tighten the law in relation to the owners of civilian weapons.
It is the response of the government authorities to recent events: cases of shooting at weddings that went by without victims, and the massacre prepared by the Moscow lawyer Dimitri Vinograd, which resulted in the deaths of seven people.
Police want to ban the carrying of dangerous weapons in public places and increase the age at which a license to carry weapons can be obtained - from 18 to 21 years.
This idea is supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaj, who promised that changes to the arms law will be submitted to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian state authorities are trying to deal with the problem by the way of "tightening the screws".
An open letter appeared on the network, whose authors - representatives of various social shooting organizations - demand the rejection of the "senseless tightening" of the law.
The percentage of hooliganism with registered weapons is minimal, said Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and criminalist in an interview with the Russian BBC.
According to statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, in the six months of 2012, 142 crimes were committed using firearms registered by the authorities of the Ministry of the Interior, while in the same period a total of 1168 thousand crimes were committed.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tighter legislation in the field of civilian weapons will not allow the perpetrator to switch to the "black" market.
According to them, any weapon can be found in Moscow at a low price.
Currently, the Ministry of the Interior claims that the situation with the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The "black" arms market is supplied by several channels.
The main channels are five, says Colonel Victor Baran<0xC4><0x9B>c, who worked for ten years at the workplaces of the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of pages that accept orders of weapons
The first of them - "military or military way", that is, a weapon that was stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"Weapons were also stolen by Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baran<0xC4><0x9B>c.
Another type of "black weapons" are weapons stolen by criminals from security forces.
Baranec explains that this includes both theft from police warehouses and weapons stolen directly from employees of the authorities involved in criminal proceedings.
Illegal "mainly" are being sold from military warehouses.
In many military warehouses, explosions often occur.
"It's been proven that some of the fires were deliberately set up - to cover up the gap," the former soldier says.
According to Barance, weapons manufacturers are also making their contribution.
“Currently, private arms companies are emerging, which are not competitive on the international market, and they are eliminating the weapons they supply to the black market, including Moscow,” said the expert.
Another source of the "black" market is smuggling.
A particularly large number of guns and vending machines come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There's their production, sometimes weapons are produced in small production, and there's the mafia that organized their smooth production," the former soldier explains.
Where's the gun from?
Experts have summed up the approximate share of individual sources of supply of illegal weapons to the "black" market.
