Among fans of modern virtual reality technologies is a popular topic of augmented reality; lately it means to perceive the world especially through the grain of special glasses.
At its annual conference at the beginning of the summer, Google presented a working model of the novelty, and in November it was announced that the application for the relevant patent was also filed by Microsoft.
A conversation with Sharam Izadi, the head of the interactive 3D technology group at Microsoft’s Cambridge Laboratory, shows that glasses are a thing of the past for the company’s scientists.
The attraction is the perspective of manipulation of virtual objects in the air with bare hands, the creation of virtual public spaces.
- Please tell us in detail, what is your research group doing?
- We deal with human-machine interactions, but at the same time we try to push the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity has so far been stuck in the stage of working with pixels on a flat screen, at most sometimes touching the screen with the finger.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead and anticipate significant changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors - this is a step forward, and almost no Xbox today is for sale without Kinect sensors, because for everyone there is a very interesting option to control using gestures.
- What else awaits us in the future?
- Despite the fact that Kinect has moved the interaction to a physical level, a lot of interactions are still taking place on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input flow of information has improved (the system receives a larger amount of data), but the output flow has not yet been significantly improved.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional imaging systems based on different technologies, including projective ones.
We need to let the computer world into our physical world, make it more real.
However, for this purpose, it is necessary to know not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we will be able to add to the real world virtual objects in a much more convenient form.
And first of all - to hell with those stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think of voice control?
That's a popular thing, but isn't it overrated?
- Certainly it cannot be considered an all-purpose remedy - the question of privacy arises, because we do not always want to inform others in our area about our activities and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but in their own environment.
For example, for controlling devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not about gestures, only about such sloppy, short ones.
The gesture would not be sensed by the device’s camera, but by a bracelet that would track the movements of the bones and muscles.
So far it is large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
In general, however, the future has a mixed type of control, such as gesture + voice.
- How do you do that?
- For example, how do you ask me to give you this can of lemonade?
You say it and you show it at the same time.
- I'm usually just talking.
- Oh, it's gonna be very difficult to recognize.
- So you want to get users to adapt to what the machine can or can't do at the moment?
- It's not necessary at all, but it's a rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that can more accurately detect human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors that provide relatively good depth resolution, this is very important.
- If you have to talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your requirements for modern cameras?
Isn't there enough resolution, depth, or something else today?
- Basically the current generation - that's what we can reflect on in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps.
But it’s not just megapixels themselves, but as nuts and depth.
With the current view of the matter, all current technologies are inadequate for us - this assigns work to algorithm designers.
So we need to keep in mind not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also Z.
So very important is also the speed, the number of frames per second.
The human movement is quite dynamic and the current data streams of 30 frames per second are frankly a little bit, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes from our Redmond lab made a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms, with current, mass-produced sensors being closer to the second value (60-100 ms).
Not everyone understands the extent to which it affects a person’s interaction with a machine.
For me, the equivalent of such a device would be very useful at work, I just don't need so many touches, but I need some snapshots per second extra.
- And there's no need to increase the number of cameras?
- There are now three "cameras" in the Kinect system, one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other - a receiver of a reflected signal.
And the third camera - this is actually a common sensor of the visible band.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
A larger number of cameras could potentially solve the problem ...
Or worsen it, because it would increase the necessary amount of calculations carried out.
It would be nice to create a flexible analog Kinect system, play with the curvature of the camera location and see how it will help in determining the three-dimensional position.
If I remember correctly, Microsoft (unlike Google) did not publicly present its glasses.
Don’t you think that when it comes to day-to-day use of augmented reality technology with special glasses, it’s one of the most promising platforms?
- Of course, walking and constantly holding the smatphone in his hands is not very comfortable, but I think: the most powerful variant would be the "portable" form of augmented reality, where it would be possible to switch from glasses to smartphones based on the clouds platform at any time, projection display and so on around.
Glasses - this is a very personal device, in which is their strength (private things you see only you), and at the same time also the weakness - augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects simultaneously with other people.
- Imagine for a moment that manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark in "Iron Man", but also to the ordinary mortal.
There is one problem that critics often point out: there is no touch response!
My hands can't feel anything!
What are your team’s responses to this challenge?
In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh consecutive breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the addition of touch sensations could easily be the eighth breakthrough.
So far, one of the interesting tricks has been used - the use of second hand as a certain type of background for display.
Excellent way to record the pressing!
But there are also technologies that are really focused on adding tactileness to these "images in the air" - for example, the interference of several directional ultrasound rays at the defined point where the finger is located, evokes a tactile feeling, but it's still very weak - as if you were blinking on your beard.
There is also a bracelet on the wrist that affects the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool your brain?
To think that he feels what he seems to feel at the moment when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another challenge that will be fought for a long time - how to make a person who is physically located in a very narrow space to believe that he is walking in an open, virtually infinite space - we are also working on the concept of running tracks (not at all such as corners as in clubs), moving platforms.
If lying to the brain becomes the target, then work is still for many years.
That’s what makes working on virtual reality so appealing to researchers – a lot of things are at the very beginning.
