Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland initiated close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in a number of ESA projects over the next few years.
However, Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts had already devoted themselves to space flight before World War II; but they did not always encounter understanding.
I recall, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933, presented ideas from his pioneering work Entry into Cosmonautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld received the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his entry into space in France.
The noted doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a major proponent of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautics and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the reverse side of the Moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a rail rail was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was to be used to start the dredge or to brake it.
Information about this draught is known only from the periodical press.
In 1933, the Polish artillery began to use missiles.
The research was carried out by the Cell of Arms Technologies in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustav Mokrzycki.
From the preserved materials, it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the professional press, and the following year, the work Rocket - an air torpedo and an aircraft rocket bomb by the author Leliwy-Krzywoblocky was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Shortly before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work, was dedicated to all projects of military use of rocket technology.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, it ended the beginning of the war.
After the war, other works on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronauticze).
For the first time, the company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, which contains four more extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, by Prof. M. Subotowiczze, is proposed the creation of a society that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, projects of artificial satellites were already taking place, and it was clear that space research is a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the autumn PTA became a regular member.
And the following year, the first president of PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became the vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has played a significant role in the development of the highly successful RM (Meteorological Rocket), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with access to 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959, two-stage RM-2 rocket flight tests were launched in the Bled Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another development type should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have access to up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the altitude wind.
However, in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM rocket was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed from 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and its starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which varied in size for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A had a capacity of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B had a capacity of 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C had a capacity of 0.62 litres.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aerospace Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
Poland joined the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and formed the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland was also involved in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites under the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second interkosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
