In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah Mohammed Réz Pahlavi, who fled to the United States after the revolution, which had been the patron saint of his regime for decades.
For the U.S. administration, the situation did not offer a positive basis - she could not afford to throw the shah overboard, as it would fundamentally jeopardize the confidence of allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, was not possible.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later further exacerbated by the fiasco of an attempt to free the hostages by force.
The detainees were finally released after 444 days after negotiations were mediated by the Algerian government.
Their fate at home evoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the loss of Jimmy Carter to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
A film directed by Ben Affleck Argo describes one episode of the story that brought America a small victory.
Six employees fled the embassy shortly before it was occupied.
After a difficult journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helping with an extravagant cover story - they went on Canadian passports as members of a film crew who were watching locations for the sci-fi film in the country.
Combination of genres
The plan, devised by Tony Mendez’s “exfiltration” expert, also required Hollywood to cooperate.
In order for the legend to be credible, it was written about a film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have been kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a peculiar combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller, at the same time the so-called "caper movie", the story of a successful piece, a hoax - an example can be Danny's series of partners.
In the film, moods alternate - on the one hand, a documentary sequence from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic time photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were shown in the film - there are no big differences).
On the other hand, a lightened passage from Hollywood, dealt with with irony and slight exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions -- men in suits discussing the situation at the meeting tables, in the hallways of the office, on the phone...
Ben Afflecki has managed to start his career in a remarkable way.
From a ridiculed actor he became a respected director and even his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third full-length film, after Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City (2010).
At the same time, it is the first Affleck film that does not take place in the director's hometown of Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that elevated the director's older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck also shows it in Arg, where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, while reconstructing real events - the opening sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive in its clarity, which at the same time conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that occur when the cleaners move more clearly.
Affleck and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in imaginary scenes (fake headquarters on the Tehran bazaar).
Too many events in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story told does not actually offer much in the film sense of thrilling scenes.
Quite successfully working with it, sometimes he thinks something to reality - there everything is no longer so elegantly (a scene in which the impending crisis at the Tehran airport distracts the phone call in America and the chase after the ranway seems quite attracted to the hair).
The weakness of Arga, however, is the frivolity that arises from the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters deserve more space and are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film loses a bit of dramatic momentum, it is a film that can be watched with a slight interest, to appreciate the realization and retro style of evocative 70s thrillers.
But it's hard to break.
