None of these old-fashioned libraries are being voluntarily visited today, are they?
Spijkenisse, a residence in close proximity to Rotterdam without its own job opportunities, which are not worth a visit, holds a special record.
This village with 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to resolve this stupid situation, a few years ago a decision was made to contribute to general education and to build seven beautifully painted concrete miniatures of fictitious bridges depicted on euro banknotes.
The success of the educational offensive, however, was not at all dizzying.
And so city councillors realized that there is only one way to become masters of statistics: we must have a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural studio MVRDV, master of insanely bold column graphs and maker of funny, often even cynical buildings, accepted the matter with the usual calm and at the competition in 2003 he appeared with five books under his arm and a smile on tv.
And while the committee still looked around and shrugged, the daring Maas made his gifts according to his size and ended his activistically justified speech with the words, "Dear City Villages!"
So this is my proposal on the Mountain of Books in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was completed for 30 million euros.
It is part of the revitalization project, which also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and townhouses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Mountain of Books was awarded the second place "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
The small-town gray, which could not yet offer more than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an unusually ugly town hall, behind whose white facade you would rather expect a dairy store, is richer with a bit of modern architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
A long way to the book
First impression: a reader's eldorado under the lid of cheeses.
You will find an elevator through the massif of the mountain, but you will discover real spatial and reader’s passions only when you walk through the topography.
The glazed interior is bright and clear on all sides, the floor made of burnt cabriolet and elegant street lanterns clearly express the atmosphere of the public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, dog and boys and girls playing football.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally there are bookshelves along the facade and in the middle there is a large dark space, which is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We built the classic spatial configuration upside down and pushed out space for the readers from the inside out.
The interior of the Mountain of Books is cleverly used: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and a home technology center.
A special delight is the black shelves for books, which are once a lining of the walls, once a parapet and sometimes a railing of stairs.
The appearance, structure and smell are foreign.
Architects and construction engineers even sworn in with their heads over unknown building materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials here,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard magazine.
So one day, at a Frisian farm, we stumbled upon a suitable agricultural waste product.
For many years, a millimeter cloth made of synthetic material has been used as a base under the roots in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It is inexpensive and time-efficient.
Thin textiles last for one, two seasons and then are ripe for disposal into bulky waste.
For the library, the cloth - for the first time in such a quantity - was pressed into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
By the action of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) is colored into a dark, homogeneous and load-bearing material that smells a little like a new car and a little like sports shoes.
After 105 steps, you get to the top.
At the end of the almost 500-metre journey, you will be rewarded not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquets and figs in flower pots.
They care about the atmosphere, but mainly about the proper humidity of the air in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for a New Soul
"You probably wouldn't believe it, but this house is an example of ecology, despite its many glass surfaces," says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled by the earth’s heat.
Although the mountain of books stands under a glass lid, the sun shines inside only briefly, even on sunny days.
Wide glued wooden brackets, perpendicular to the glazed facade, serve as a shading and capture much of the sun’s rays.
The air in the room is very pleasant.
With the rest, they can handle fully automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, an early skeptic in the IT industry, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde, who even refers to Boekenberg as the "long-awaited soul" of Spijkenisse.
Reason: Every city dweller was invited to open a book from his personal fund a few weeks ago.
Thus, the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library, which currently consists of 70,000 pieces, were to be filled first.
The concept has proven itself.
The shelves are full.
“There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with the new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it was just for decoration.
Thus, the MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which in professional jargon is called the formation of identity.
Spijkenisse wrote the history of literature.
No matter how young or unskilled.
This is, after all, the starting point for identity.
