"In fact, boredom has a long history," he said.
On the walls of Pompeii was found a Latin inscription concerning boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there is the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After looking at the research literature and showing the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I wasn't able to."
Boredom differs from apathy in that a person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says there's no compulsion to do anything with apathy.
He says that the core of boredom is “a disruption of the process of attention, associated with a bad mood and a feeling of slowly passing time.”
Boredom can be very similar to depression.
