Sometimes we think we’re bored when we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention” published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to a previous experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which a person read an article from the magazine.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group did not hear it at all.
Those who listened to the TV show quietly reported more boredom than the other two groups – they had difficulty concentrating, but were unsure of why, and attributed these difficulties to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or tempting task, distractions can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
