The judgment approved by the U.S. Court of Appeal, which does not recognise the restructuring of Grupo Vitro’s debt imposed by the bankruptcy in Mexico, creates a bad precedent for any national enterprise with branches in a neighboring country and a solvency problem.
Thus, it seems that the procedures for restructuring companies that allow Mexican laws do not apply in a country of stripes and stars, despite international agreements.
Approval of a judgment issued on June 15 last year by Judge Harlin Hale at the North Texas bankruptcy court leaves Mexican firms in practice defenseless against the possibility of confiscating their property on the other side of the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door for the main Mexican glass manufacturer to the United States Supreme Court with an appeal against three irregularities.
In the introduction, while the judge of the case claims that creditors should abide by the U.S. insolvency law, the Fifth District Court of Appeal, based in New Orleans, says that the main proceeding provides for bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
First, it would indicate the ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
Essentially, a United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created for this purpose, which is arbitrated by the American Law Institute.
Secondly, the judgment provides that without the vote of the branches of the internal business structure, where the debt of the parent company Vitro to the branches is recognised, the required majority for the approval of the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, Mexican laws allow for this possibility.
The fact is that the case of Vitro was not the first in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples such as Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, for which domestic debts were guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Institute.
Moreover, it is true that even after deducting the votes of the branches, creditors - who opposed Vitro in the United States, i.e. the funds of "supposes", such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not have achieved the majority.
In the vote, they would reach about 45 percent to 37.
This fact is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
From a different point of view, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 – against the backdrop of a serious economic crisis that has hit the United States.
Meanwhile, the family-owned company González Sady will appeal to the Court of Appeal for a new review, so that the review will take place with the full participation, that is, with the participation of five judges, because originally only three voted.
If it fails here, it will seek as a remedy the review of the process by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
The seriousness of the case is that the court omitted a document sent by the Mexican government as the amicus curiae department, which detailed the procedure of Vitro under the Bankruptcy Act and pointed out that the company facilitated the state by adhering to the agreements signed by both countries.
In addition, it points out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. rules for international insolvency cases that guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
