Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Basketball world champion Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has been associated with this indoor sport for more than 60 years and has travelled the world thanks to it.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of the history of local basketball as Hector "Hetin" Reyes has.
Reyes had been involved in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a junior player, a BSN national basketball league player, the owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayamón team in the national basketball league, or the president of the Portor basket.
"I've played a lot of roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, like when I was the president of the BSN National League in the 1990s, the general manager of the national team and the president of the federation," Reyes recalled when visiting reporters of the Primer Hora newspaper.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate his claim.
The walls of his house, which are almost all decorated with photos and souvenirs from his long career, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
With the greatest excitement of all, he guards those reminiscent of his time in Los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, when he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as co-owner or owner of the team.
“It’s been my best years, the one I’ve enjoyed the most because I’ve had the opportunity to participate in eight championships with the Los Vaqueros since 1967, whether as an owner, co-owner or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held between 1971 and 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship - in 1981, when Jerome Mincy made his BSN debut.
At that time, the team took over "Cuco" Ortiz, who was an excellent manager," Reyes said.
“I remember Gene Bartow, who was a former coach here and was working at the University of Alabama in Birmingham at the time, saying to me, ‘I have a grown-up two-meter player for you.
You want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended me player Raymond Gauss, who became a member of the team and one of our best shooters.
I remember saying that if Mincy brings Bayamon a championship victory, then Gauss will contribute to another."
The championship, where Los Vaqueros played for Gauss, was enjoyed, but only at a distance, because in 1988 he already served as president of the basketball federation.
At that time, he wanted to devote himself fully to his functions and enjoy Mincy’s place in the national team.
“I remember defeating the United States for the first time in the qualifying game in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished quarterfinals, but we should have had the bronze without that Canadian referee who let us repeat the final throw," Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
He is among the best, just like the one who defeated the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the national team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won the gold and scratched the U.S. team that was pretty similar to the one that blew us the bronze at the World Cup.
The team had not only Mincy, Gauss, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculina" (Ortiz), but also there were youngsters (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be in the team because of the turn in 1990.
The team that may not have the perfect composition, but was able to win a gold medal and bring us great joy, was the team from the 1995 Olympic qualification in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players on the roster such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner replacing players excluded due to a fight at the Pan American Games in Mar de Plata, we won gold despite all predictions.
What was the best player in Puerto Rico?
It was undoubtedly Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers from international tournaments are impressive.
No one from Puerto Rico has achieved such results at this level as Piculin.
Not to mention his work in various leagues where he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican coach?
That's very hard.
We had a very good generation, including Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armandito Torres.
I really like the work of Leo Arilla.
Which do you consider your success in the federation to be the greatest?
That I was part of the most famous era of the national team from 1988 to 1995 and that in the early 1990s the BSN national league had up to 17 teams in one season.
What have you failed to prove?
There were things that I wanted to introduce, like the division of youth categories by regions.
For example, the Ponce boys would only play in their area and compete with teams from other corners of the island only in national play-offs.
Now children travel a lot and play too many matches, which is not necessary.
I also see a contribution in compulsory certificates and courses for coaches, referee assistants and referees.
I'm glad to hear that.
What are you doing now?
I mostly listen to music, watch YouTube videos with music from my time, enjoy having grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball games.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, became world-renowned as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the Dallas television series, in which he portrayed a man who acted ruthlessly and was insidious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role of predatory oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the Dallas TV series became a symbol of hunger in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned as J.R. in the new Dallas series this year, died on Friday afternoon from complications related to cancer, according to the family's official announcement provided to the Associated Press by Dallas production company Warner Bros..
“Larry returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he loved most,” the family said.
Larry's family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas on Thanksgiving.
"Linda Gray, who was his wife's representative in both the original and the new series, was with Hagman at the time of his death at the Dallas hospital," her agent Jeffrey Lane said in a statement.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
"He was creative, generous, funny, kind, kind and talented, and I will miss him so much.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest," Linda Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he himself admitted that he had been drinking a lot for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before the Dallas series aired, Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy I Dream of Jeannie aired by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (Genie) played by Barbara Eden and takes her home to live together.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, The Good Life (NBC, 1971–72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His performances in films included roles that were well received by critics: The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it wasn’t until Hangman’s masterful performance in the form of an incredibly repulsive J.R. that took him to the stellar peak.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other personalities around them was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan “Who Shot Jair?”, which was supposed to evoke expectations about the emotion-filled part of the Hangman character being nearly murdered, has caused not only a huge array of speculation from viewers around the world, but also the risk of millions of dollars in tax offices.
This also helped this piece to achieve a track record.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, was watched by an average of 41 million television viewers, making Dallas the second most watched entertainment show in history after the 1983 MASH series, which was watched by 50 million viewers.
J.R. was shot by his sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin got pregnant with J.R. and he threatened to call her a prostitute if she didn't leave town, but there were others who had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, an insatiable greedy man with a charismatic smile: a deceitful businessman and unfaithful husband who tried to get his wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), who was an alcoholic, locked up in a nursing home.
"I know what I want J.R. to have on the gravestone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be, "Here lies the honorable citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only thing that didn't work out.
Victoria Principal, who played in the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone who was "great on-screen and off-screen."
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of admirers in the world and in the hearts of all of us who have had the good fortune to know and love him.
Ten parts of the new Dallas series were broadcast by TNT a few months ago with great success.
"Five episodes of the second series have already been filmed and the sixth has just been filmed," the broadcaster said.
Immediately after Hangman's death, there was no statement from Warner or TNT about how the series would continue.
A cousin from Fort Worth, Texas, was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in classics such as the South Pacific and Peter Pan musicals.
Mary Martin was a very young girl when she gave birth to Larry in 1931, whose father was her husband, lawyer Ben Hagman.
In the early 1950s, Larry tried his luck on stages in New York City, and then served in the British Air Force from 1952 to 1956.
There he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson, whom he married.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities live.
In 2001, he published the autobiographical book Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
"I didn't put anything in there that I knew could hurt someone or hurt them in any way," he told Prensa Asociada.
After a liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in a hospital where he helped fearful patients.
"I advise them, I give them courage, I meet them when they go to surgery and then," he said in 1996.
I try to give them comfort in the sense of "don't worry, it will be a little uncomfortable for a while, but you'll be healthy".
He was also an anti-smoking activist and participated in various campaigns.
Starting a course that explores the "end of the world"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided that this semester would take a course on the end of the world, he knew that it was an irresistible attraction: The end of the “long number” of the Mayan calendar, due on December 21, caught many people as proof that the end of the world was coming.
Charmé, however, had no idea what was ahead of him in the next few months: Catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a budget gap that some call "the debt Armageddon," and the growing conflict in which Israel is drawn, a place where, according to Christians theorizing the end of the Apocalypse, the world begins.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey.
When you think about what’s going on in the world today as if you have 30 days left, it’s a really good time.
And remember, bad means good for apocalyptic thinkers.
And he’s not the only professor to offer courses on the “end of the world” this semester, which is theoretically the latest in history.
At Temple University, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker holds a course "Resources, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
“We’re discussing why these ideas expand over time,” he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that govern certain human behavior.
If, for example, nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, a war may erupt.
This month, students are analyzing movies with apocalyptic themes and exploring how they differ from real-life examples.
“I tried to inform students about what is possible, probable, credible, and impossible,” says Vacker.
At Pennsylvania State University’s main campus, professor of Latin American history Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solario, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, came together to organize a course called The End of the World.
“We don’t add ‘2012’ because we always count on the possibility of arranging the course again if the world doesn’t end,” Restall said.
Despite the "threatening destruction", students must study, create projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will take place on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work “until the evening of the world’s expected end,” Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
"It stretched into two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, who enrolled 35.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we were asked by e-mail whether there was still room.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves," said 23-year-old Bridgid Robinson, a religion and sociology student at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey.
Therefore, apocalyptic, secular or religious thinking is only a matter of consolation or its absence.
Will Wekes, a 25-year-old student of psychology and nursing, said he had seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I've never heard of an hour before when this could be taught," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But no confessed student, let alone a professor, said he believed in the date of the end of December 21st.
“Our first project was about Mayan predictions, and we’re going to somehow refute it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old undergraduate at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that in Western culture there is an apocalyptic anxiety that dates back several centuries, which people react to the changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has sparked these speculations.
"People don't think about it elsewhere," he said.
This happens in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University, who is giving a lecture in the Philippines this year, when asked if he knew of any course there about the "end of the world," answered quickly.
"The Philippines will not participate in the end of the world," he wrote, suggesting an exception to the Supreme Authority.
We have the grace of the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there was talk of many days of the Last Judgment, saying that if nothing happens on December 21st, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21st is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will end.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors.
Several of them said they intend to go to the celebration of the "end of the world".
"I'll probably call a few friends to laugh together," 20-year-old communication student Samira Ford said.
